title: Scoundrel
author: Sarah Weinman
review: Fascinating book about a sociopath

title: Three Body Problem
author: Cixin Liu
review: Ending was good.  First 3/4 of the book were not very interesting.  Story was hard to follow with all chinese character names.

title: The Elegant Universe
author: Brian Greene
review: Good book but you can get lost in some places.

title: Going Infinite
author: Michael Lewis
review: Consummate story teller

title: The Order of Time
author: Carlo Rovelli
review: Too much philosophy and not enough science.  Too abstract.

title: Only Say Good Things
author: Crystal Hefner
review: Expected but eye opening book.

title: Omnivore's Dilemma
author: Michael Pollan
review: Good book - section on foraging/hunting was a little dry.

title: Fire Weather: A True Story from a Hotter World
author: John Vaillant
review: Great book about Fort McMurray and climate science and its affects.

title: In Defense of Food
author: Michael Pollan
review: Great quick read about the dangers of nutritionism and eating whole foods.

title: Math with Bad Drawings
author: Ben Orlin
review: Smart, funny, and insightful book about the nuances of life and relation to math.

title: Beautyland
author: Marie-Helene Burtino
review: Very distinctive writing style.  Good book about reflections of human life and intracacies.

title: Eruption
author: Michael Crichton
review: Entertaining book that had good pace.

title: Phantom Orbit
author: David Ignatius
review: Fascinating interplay between real events and fictional story.

title: Rental House
author: Weike Wang
review: I gave it 4 stars - I wouldn’t read it again.  I like the writing style as it was very entertaining but I didn’t get the point.  It just seemed like a tragic comedy of a millennial biracial couple.

title: You Are Not So Smart
author: David McRaney
review: Decently good psychology book that goes over many of the biases you experience on a daily basis and other fallacies.

title: You Like It Darker
author: Stephen King
review: A collection of short stories.  Overall pretty engaging and interesting stories.  Nothing groundbreaking but it was a page turner and i would definitely read again for entertainment.

title: A Talent for Murder
author: Peter Swanson
review: I thought it was just a good entertaining read! keeps your attention and has good pace!

title: The Anxious Generation
author: Jonathan Haidt
review: I'm not normally a fan of pyschology books but this one was really good.  No need to read again but it was very insightful about the dangers of phones and social media to young kids.

title: The God of the Woods
author: Liz Moore
review: Really entertaining and captivating book with lots of twists and turns.

title: Die With Zero
author: Bill Perkins
review: A good concept but from the perspective of someone who doesn't need to save another penny for his life. So of course he wants to invest in experiences.  I'm not sure who the targes audience is: I would imagine not too many 20 somethings would read this book but the messages of risk taking and investing in life experiences are directed towards that cohort.  But it is never too late to start.
